<HEADLINE>
<P>
4-YEAR-OLD'S LAWSUIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to "Paralyzed Girl Sues to Attend Local School," (Metro, Sept. 5): 
</P>
<P>
Four steps and a Los Angeles Unified School District policy are preventing 
Xochitl Soto from attending Bushnell Way School, three blocks from her home. 
The 4-year-old preschooler must use a wheelchair for mobility and the school 
isn't ramped. 
</P>
<P>
Of the two obstacles, the policy is the larger barrier because it is based on 
centuries of people with disabilities being viewed as less than people without 
disabilities and, therefore, not entitled to the same treatment. 
</P>
<P>
It is not complicated to build a ramp. It is hard to admit that a policy has 
been based on a prejudiced interpretation of a federal law. 
</P>
<P>
The recent passage of the Americans With Disabilities Act says to society that 
individuals with disabilities are now guaranteed the same basic civil rights as 
everyone else. 
</P>
<P>
MARY ANN ELLEFSON 
</P>
<P>
Burbank 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Xochitl Soto, her attorney Paul Miller and Xochitl's older brother, 
Moses. RICK MEYER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
