<HEADLINE>
<P>
MANDATORY STATE QUAKE INSURANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is remarkable that the Legislature has made allowances for the provision of 
over $25,000 insurance coverage for every California homeowner against 
earthquake damage; all for $36 a year (Part A, Aug. 28). 
</P>
<P>
Legislators are to be congratulated on the one hand and admonished on the 
other. 
</P>
<P>
In a state of more than 28 million, approximately 5 million are uninsured for 
medical care. This includes a significant number of blue- and white-collar 
workers who either choose not to or cannot find affordable medical insurance. 
</P>
<P>
It must be clearly understood that a significant part of the high cost of 
medical care for all Californians occurs as a result of the economic loss 
suffered by hospitals and health-care providers in caring for those patients 
who are uninsured. 
</P>
<P>
This injustice to the health and well-being of our citizens, who predictably 
will require medical care, is underscored by the compassion shown toward the 
potential for damages from an earthquake that may never occur or cause serious 
or significant personal and economic injuries. 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL H. SUKOFF, MD 
</P>
<P>
Santa Ana 
</P>
</TEXT>
