<HEADLINE>
<P>
EXCELLENCE CLOSE TO HOME; 
</P>
<P>
INCREASING THE TALENT POOL WHERE IT HAS BEEN MOST NEGLECTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
These days, the state of public schools in Los Angeles -- indeed, nationwide -- 
is not usually a subject that elicits cheers. But there's a new public school 
in East Los Angeles that does just that. 
</P>
<P>
It's Francisco Bravo Medical Magnet High School, a privately financed, 
$45-million-dollar school that was built in 27 months on 3.5 acres of land. It 
proves, says board of education member Roberta Weintraub, that new public 
schools don't have to take five years to build and don't need mammoth plots of 
land. It should be a model for private-public partnerships in improving 
education, Weintraub says. She's right. 
</P>
<P>
But Bravo Medical Magnet does even more. It encourages and trains future 
physicians and medical technicians. Bravo and a similar school, the smaller 
King/Drew Medical Magnet High School in South Los Angeles, are increasing the 
pool of talent where it has been most neglected: among Latinos and blacks. 
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 students attend Bravo; the curriculum includes courses not usually 
taught in high school, including classes in biomedical research and nursing. It 
also has an affiliation with Los Angeles County/USC Medical Center that will 
give students greater exposure to the real world of medicine. 
</P>
<P>
While the school is open to students throughout the district, its Eastside 
location is close to the homes of many Latinos, who make up about 56% of the 
students. (King Drew also draws students from all over the city; 60% of its 
students are African-American). 
</P>
<P>
More than examples of what can be right about public education, these schools 
are crucial to the nation's increasingly high-tech future. The fast-growing 
number of Latino and black children are seriously under-represented in the math 
and science fields. Thus the creation of more Latino and black scientists, 
mathematicians, nurses and physicians becomes not only a matter of community 
pride but national necessity. 
</P>
<P>
Bravo will help make a difference, and to that we say -- what else? Bravo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
