<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A City Heights man convicted of involuntary manslaughter was sentenced to three 
years in state prison Thursday in the April 22 death of a 12-year-old girl who 
jumped from his truck on Interstate 5 to her death. 
</P>
<P>
Two relatives of the girl made outbursts in court and left the courtroom during 
the sentencing of Jesus Hector Garcia Artega, 28. 
</P>
<P>
Garcia also was fined $1,200 by San Diego Superior Court Judge William Mudd. 
</P>
<P>
Garcia pleaded guilty in July to involuntary manslaughter in the death of 
Sylvia Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
As Garcia's attorney, Alex Loebig asked about a dozen relatives of Garcia to 
stand in court to show their support, relatives of the slain girl said that 
they should also be acknowledged. 
</P>
<P>
Mudd told the packed courtroom that anyone who spoke out during the sentencing 
would be ordered to leave. The judge then asked that the victim's relatives 
also stand. 
</P>
<P>
Garcia told the judge he "never tried to hurt anyone." 
</P>
<P>
Loebig conceded that Garcia "acted irresponsibly" by not stopping or returning 
to the scene after the girl jumped out of the car. 
</P>
