<HEADLINE>
<P>
INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION DECLINED LAST MONTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Industrial production dropped 0.2% in August, the worst monthly performance 
since a 0.2% decline in April, the Federal Reserve said today. 
</P>
<P>
It was the government's first report on the manufacturing sector since the 
Persian Gulf crisis, and economists had expressed concern over the effect of 
sharply higher energy prices on factory activity. 
</P>
<P>
Industrial production had been sluggish even before the Iraqi invasion of 
Kuwait, although it had fallen only twice previously this year, in April and in 
January. It was unchanged in July. 
</P>
<P>
Output of durable goods, motor vehicles and other big-ticket items was off 0.2% 
on top of a 0.3% decline in July. Manufacturing of non-durable goods such as 
food and clothing was unchanged after a 0.5% gain a month earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
